    dissectionAndExperiment: [
        "Dissect the clonal selection theory mechanistically: (a) explain what generates the pre-existing diversity of lymphocyte receptors (V(D)J recombination); (b) explain what determines which clone is selected (antigen-receptor complementarity); (c) explain what drives clonal expansion (cytokines — especially IL-2 for T cells; T cell help for B cells); (d) explain what drives differentiation into effector vs memory cells (cytokine milieu, transcription factor expression). Connect each component to a specific molecular mechanism — do not leave any step as a black box.",
        "Dissect the two-signal model of T cell activation: signal 1 = TCR binding antigen-MHC complex (antigen-specific); signal 2 = CD28 binding B7 on APC (antigen-nonspecific co-stimulation). Outcome with both signals: full T cell activation and IL-2 production. Outcome with signal 1 only: anergy (T cell becomes unresponsive). Outcome with neither: T cell remains naive. Connect signal 2 requirement to the clinical use of CTLA-4-Ig (abatacept) in autoimmunity — blocking B7 suppresses T cell activation in auto-reactive states.",
        "Dissect an ELISA experiment step by step: (1) antigen coating (capture) — explain why antigen adheres to plastic; (2) blocking step — explain what non-specific binding is and why it must be prevented; (3) patient serum addition — explain what determines which antibodies bind; (4) wash step — explain why this removes background; (5) secondary antibody addition — explain what the secondary antibody recognises (primary antibody Fc region); (6) enzyme substrate addition — explain how enzyme amplification increases sensitivity. Connect each step to a fundamental antibody property.",
        "Dissect a checkpoint inhibitor clinical scenario: (a) identify which checkpoint is being blocked (PD-1, PD-L1, or CTLA-4); (b) identify the normal physiological function of that checkpoint; (c) explain why blocking it releases anti-tumour T cells; (d) explain why the same mechanism causes immune-related adverse events; (e) explain why not all tumour types respond (connect to tumour mutational burden, MHC expression, and pre-existing T cell infiltrate). Use this five-step framework for any checkpoint inhibitor question.",
        "Dissect the mechanics of affinity maturation in germinal centres: naive B cell enters germinal centre → activation-induced cytidine deaminase (AID) introduces somatic point mutations into variable region genes → some mutations increase affinity (better binding to antigen displayed on follicular dendritic cells) → those B cells survive and proliferate; lower-affinity mutants undergo apoptosis → repeated cycles increase average antibody affinity over days to weeks. Connect this to why secondary response antibodies have higher affinity than primary response antibodies and why this matters for protection."
    ]
