    dissectionAndExperiment: [
        "Dissect the ATP accounting step by step: write out all ten steps in a table. For each step, enter the ATP or NADH change per triose phosphate in the payoff phase, remembering to multiply by two for glucose (both trioses). Sum each column separately: ATP consumed (steps 1 and 3: −1 each = −2 total per glucose), ATP produced (steps 7 and 10: +1 each × 2 trioses = +4 total), NADH produced (step 6: +1 × 2 trioses = +2 total). Net: +2 ATP, +2 NADH. At each step explain in words why the count changes or stays the same.",
        "Dissect PFK-1's allosteric regulation at the molecular level: (a) identify the allosteric site as physically separate from the active site; (b) explain that ATP acts as both substrate (binds active site) and inhibitor (binds allosteric site at high concentration); (c) draw the enzyme in T-state (inhibited, low activity, substrate cannot bind productively) and R-state (active, substrate binds); (d) explain how AMP displaces the T-state equilibrium toward R-state; (e) explain why this means the enzyme is essentially a molecular ATP-sensor.",
        "Dissect the Warburg effect at four levels of description: (1) observation — cancer cells produce lactate with oxygen present; (2) enzyme level — GLUT1 and HK2 overexpressed, PFK-1 allosteric inhibition by ATP reduced; (3) signalling level — HIF-1α transcription factor upregulates glycolytic genes; (4) evolutionary/adaptive level — aerobic glycolysis provides biosynthetic precursors (ribose-5-P, NADPH, G3P for lipids) for rapid proliferation rather than maximising ATP. Write one sentence at each level, then connect them as a causal chain.",
        "Dissect a published Lineweaver-Burk experiment on PFK-1 inhibition by ATP: (a) identify whether ATP increases apparent Km or decreases Vmax; (b) identify whether the x-intercept or y-intercept changes; (c) determine the inhibition type; (d) compare this to what you would predict for a strictly competitive inhibitor of the F6P binding site; (e) evaluate whether the data are consistent with ATP acting as an allosteric (not active site) inhibitor. Conclude with one sentence on the therapeutic implication of ATP being both substrate and allosteric inhibitor.",
        "Dissect the Cori cycle energetically: (a) glycolysis in muscle: 2 ATP per glucose, 2 lactate produced; (b) lactate transport to liver: MCT4 exports, MCT1/2 imports, energy cost negligible; (c) gluconeogenesis in liver: 6 ATP + 2 GTP consumed per glucose synthesised from 2 lactate; (d) glucose transport back to muscle: GLUT2 exports from liver, GLUT4 imports into muscle (insulin-dependent). Net energy transfer: muscle gains 2 ATP at the cost of 8 high-energy phosphates in the liver. Calculate the efficiency ratio and explain why the liver accepts this cost during exercise."
    ]
