    dissectionAndExperiment: [
        "Dissect the ATP hydrolysis exergonicity from first principles: draw three resonance structures of Pi (orthophosphate) and compare to the restricted resonance of the γ-phosphate in ATP (constrained by the adjacent phosphate). Count the stable resonance contributors for each. Identify that more resonance structures for the products = greater resonance stabilisation = lower free energy of products = more negative ΔG. Then add the solvation argument: Pi is better hydrated than the terminal phosphate in ATP because it is smaller and more freely accessible to water.",
        "Dissect the Mitchell chemiosmotic theory step by step using Boyer and Mitchell's own logic: (1) ETC is located asymmetrically in the membrane; (2) electron transfer is coupled to proton translocation; (3) protons cannot re-enter except via ATP synthase; (4) proton flow through ATP synthase provides the energy for phosphorylation. For each step, write the experimental observation that confirmed it (e.g. reconstitution experiments showing that orientation of ATP synthase determines which side ATP is made on).",
        "Dissect the binding change mechanism with a rotation diagram: draw three sequential diagrams showing the γ subunit at 0°, 120°, and 240° positions. For each position, label all three β subunit states. Write the chemical event occurring in each β subunit (ADP + Pi binding; ATP synthesis; ATP release) for each rotation position. At the end, confirm that one full rotation (360°) produces three ATP molecules — matching the known c-ring stoichiometry of ~8–15 subunits per full rotation per 2–3 H⁺ per subunit.",
        "Dissect cyanide toxicology mechanistically: (1) CN⁻ binds Fe³⁺ in cytochrome a₃ (Complex IV) — identify this as competitive with O₂; (2) electron flow stops; (3) proton pumping at Complex IV stops; (4) PMF decreases; (5) ATP synthase slows; (6) [ATP] falls; (7) glycolysis accelerates (AMPK and [ADP] rise); (8) NADH accumulates (no Complex I activity); (9) lactate dehydrogenase regenerates NAD⁺ → lactate accumulates. For each step, write the biochemical consequence and how it connects to the clinical signs (lactic acidosis, bright red venous blood, rapid loss of consciousness).",
        "Perform a virtual mitochondrial respiration experiment using Seahorse XF Analyser software simulation (available at several online teaching platforms): measure oxygen consumption rate (OCR) and extracellular acidification rate (ECAR) under sequential additions of oligomycin, FCCP (uncoupler), and rotenone/antimycin (ETC inhibitors). Identify from the trace: basal respiration, ATP-linked respiration (drop with oligomycin), maximal respiration (increase with FCCP), and non-mitochondrial respiration (remaining OCR after rotenone/antimycin). Calculate the spare respiratory capacity and the coupling efficiency from the trace."
    ]
