    practiceRoutines: [
        "Sensitisation-elicitation pathway reconstruction drill: from memory, reproduce the full two-phase pathway as a labelled diagram in under 5 minutes. Include: first allergen exposure → APC → Th2 → IL-4 → B cell → IgE → FcεRI → mast cell arming (sensitisation); second exposure → IgE cross-linking → FcεRI aggregation → Ca²⁺ → degranulation → mediator release → clinical symptoms (elicitation). Check against your notes. Repeat until 100% accurate.",
        "Hypersensitivity classification drill: read 10 clinical vignettes (varied onset, mediator, and organ system). For each, classify as type I, II, III, or IV and write a two-sentence mechanistic justification before checking the answer. Track error rate by type and focus repeat practice on the type most frequently misclassified.",
        "Anaphylaxis management sprint: given a clinical scenario, write the complete first-line management in under 90 seconds — drug, dose (adult and paediatric), route, site, and first adjunct. Practise with scenarios varying in trigger (food, drug, venom, latex) and setting (school, community, hospital). Verify against current national anaphylaxis guidelines.",
        "Treatment mechanism matching drill: given 10 allergy symptoms (e.g. 'wheeze unresponsive to antihistamine', 'chronic urticaria', 'atopic dermatitis refractory to topical steroids', 'acute hypotension'), identify the most appropriate intervention and its mechanism in one sentence for each. Include both pharmacological and immunotherapy options.",
        "Biologic selection practice: given five patient profiles (varying IgE levels, eosinophil counts, conditions, and prior treatment failures), select the most appropriate biologic for each and justify using the target molecule, mechanism, and expected immunological change. Practise until you can match biologic to profile in under 30 seconds per patient."
    ],

    dissectionAndExperiment: [
        "Dissect the adrenaline mechanism at receptor level for each anaphylaxis symptom: for hypotension — which receptor, which vessel, which second messenger (α1 → IP3/DAG → smooth muscle contraction → vasoconstriction → ↑SVR → ↑BP); for bronchoconstriction — β2 → adenylyl cyclase → cAMP → PKA → smooth muscle relaxation → bronchodilation; for cardiac depression — β1 → adenylyl cyclase → cAMP → increased heart rate and contractility. For each: receptor → second messenger → cellular effect → clinical reversal. Connect each to why adrenaline cannot be replaced by a single-receptor drug in anaphylaxis.",
        "Dissect the Michaelis-Menten analogy applied to receptor pharmacology: treat the H1 receptor as an enzyme and histamine as substrate — antihistamine as a competitive inhibitor. Discuss: (a) does increasing histamine concentration eventually overcome antihistamine? (b) What does this imply about antihistamine dosing in severe allergy? (c) Why do leukotrienes produce symptoms that antihistamines cannot block? This exercise connects enzyme pharmacology directly to allergy treatment logic.",
        "Dissect a clinical immunotherapy trial: find the SCIT or SLIT data for house dust mite allergy (published literature). Identify: (a) primary endpoint (symptom score vs immunological marker); (b) allergen-specific IgE change at 1 year; (c) IgG4 change at 1 year; (d) Treg count change if reported; (e) symptom score change vs placebo. Assess whether the immunological changes precede, accompany, or follow clinical benefit — this reveals the mechanism timeline of tolerance induction.",
        "Dissect the cross-reactivity mechanism in latex-fruit syndrome: identify three latex proteins (Hev b 5, Hev b 6, Hev b 7) and their homologous proteins in banana, avocado, and kiwi. Explain why IgE raised against Hev b 6 (a class I chitinase) cross-reacts with chitinases in these fruits. Connect this to the concept of epitope structure — same 3D binding site on different proteins from different species. This demonstrates that IgE specificity is for molecular shape, not biological origin.",
        "Perform an in silico mast cell degranulation simulation: using an interactive immunology animation (e.g. Nature Reviews Immunology supplementary animations or university virtual lab), observe: (a) IgE binding to FcεRI; (b) allergen cross-linking; (c) calcium influx; (d) granule fusion; (e) mediator release. Pause at each step, draw the molecular event, and annotate which drug or treatment blocks that step. Connect each step to one clinical intervention in the treatment pyramid."
    ]
