        "Create a four-column comparison table of central vs peripheral tolerance: rows = location, cell type deleted/suppressed, mechanism, monogenic disease when disrupted, consequence of failure. Use APECED for central failure and IPEX for peripheral failure as anchors.",
        "Create a five-column biologic therapy comparison table: rows = infliximab, etanercept, adalimumab, rituximab, abatacept, tocilizumab, secukinumab. Columns: (1) target molecule or cell; (2) mechanism of action; (3) approved autoimmune disease; (4) specific infection risk; (5) monitoring requirement. Complete all cells — do not leave blanks.",
        "Create a comparison table of blocking vs stimulating autoantibody diseases: rows = myasthenia gravis, Graves' disease, type B insulin resistance (anti-insulin receptor stimulatory). Columns: (1) target receptor; (2) antibody mechanism; (3) functional consequence; (4) what happens if antibody is passively transferred to a healthy person; (5) treatment approach. This table is particularly useful for mechanistic exam questions about autoantibody pathophysiology.",
        "Create a comparison table of the three mechanisms of peripheral tolerance breakdown: rows = molecular mimicry, bystander activation, epitope spreading. Columns: (1) trigger; (2) whether antigen similarity is required; (3) time course; (4) disease example; (5) why it is difficult to treat once established. Note which mechanism is reversible vs self-perpetuating."
