    dissectionAndExperiment: [
        "Dissect the HIT formula algebraically: starting from the definition of Rₑ = R₀ × (1 − p) where p = proportion immune, set Rₑ = 1 (threshold for epidemic control) and solve for p. Show every algebraic step. Then derive numerically: for measles (R₀ = 15), show that a population with 93.3% immunity gives Rₑ = 15 × (1 − 0.933) = 15 × 0.067 = 1.0. For 88% immunity: Rₑ = 15 × 0.12 = 1.8 > 1. This derivation explains mathematically why an 88% vaccination rate permits measles outbreaks.",
        "Dissect penicillin's mechanism step by step: (1) beta-lactam ring structurally mimics the D-Ala-D-Ala terminus of peptidoglycan precursor; (2) transpeptidase (PBP) attempts to bind penicillin as substrate; (3) penicillin forms a covalent acyl-enzyme intermediate with the active-site serine; (4) the beta-lactam ring opens and the acyl-enzyme does not turn over — enzyme is permanently inactivated; (5) cell wall synthesis stops; (6) ongoing membrane pressure causes osmotic lysis in dividing cells. At each step, connect to an analogous enzyme inhibition concept (step 3–4 = suicide inhibition; step 2 = competitive mimicry of natural substrate).",
        "Dissect the Gram stain procedure mechanistically: (1) crystal violet applied — stains all cells purple; (2) iodine mordant applied — crystal violet-iodine complex forms in cells; (3) decoloriser (acetone-alcohol) applied — dissolves lipid outer membrane of Gram-negative bacteria, flushing out the complex through the thin peptidoglycan layer; thick peptidoglycan of Gram-positive bacteria traps the complex — Gram-positives remain purple; (4) safranin counterstain — Gram-negative cells (now colourless) stain pink. Connect to antibiotic targeting: the Gram-negative outer membrane acts as a permeability barrier and is why many antibiotics effective against Gram-positives fail against Gram-negatives.",
        "Dissect the complement classical pathway step by step: (1) IgM or IgG antibody binds antigen on pathogen surface; (2) C1q binds the Fc region of antibody → C1q, C1r, C1s complex activates; (3) C1s cleaves C4 → C4a (inflammatory mediator) + C4b (binds pathogen surface); (4) C4b recruits C2 → C1s cleaves C2 → C4b2a (C3 convertase) forms on pathogen surface; (5) C3 convertase cleaves C3 → C3a (anaphylatoxin: recruits neutrophils) + C3b (opsonin: binds Fc receptors on phagocytes); (6) C3b joins C4b2a → C5 convertase; (7) C5 → C5a (potent anaphylatoxin) + C5b; (8) C5b initiates MAC (C5b-C9) assembly → pore in bacterial membrane → lysis. At each step, annotate the clinical consequence of deficiency in that component.",
        "Dissect a published Phase 3 vaccine trial (select any published RCT): identify and annotate — primary endpoint definition; how vaccine efficacy (VE = 1 − [attack rate vaccinated / attack rate placebo]) was calculated; confidence intervals and what they indicate about precision; subgroup analyses and whether they were pre-specified; duration of follow-up relative to expected duration of protection; whether the trial was conducted in the same population as the intended deployment. Evaluate whether the trial's efficacy estimate would be expected to match real-world effectiveness."
    ]
